Cell[TextData[{
 "Beno\[IHat]t Mandelbrot died on October 14, 2010, at the age of 85. He is \
being remembered worldwide: ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["The New York Times",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/17/us/17mandelbrot.html"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/17/us/17mandelbrot.html"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["Nature",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://blogs.nature.com/news/thegreatbeyond/2010/10/benoit_\
mandelbrot_father_of_fr.html"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "http://blogs.nature.com/news/thegreatbeyond/2010/10/benoit_mandelbrot_\
father_of_fr.html"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["Wired",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.wired.com/geekdad/2010/10/he-gave-us-order-out-of-chaos-r-\
i-p-benoit-mandelbrot-1924-2010/"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "http://www.wired.com/geekdad/2010/10/he-gave-us-order-out-of-chaos-r-i-p-\
benoit-mandelbrot-1924-2010/"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["Popular Science",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.popsci.com/science/article/2010-10/celebrating-benoit-\
mandelbrot-man-who-made-math-beautiful"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "http://www.popsci.com/science/article/2010-10/celebrating-benoit-\
mandelbrot-man-who-made-math-beautiful"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["BBC News",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-11560110"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-11560110"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["PCWorld",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.pcworld.com/article/208073/father_of_fractal_geometry_\
passes_at_age_85.html"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "http://www.pcworld.com/article/208073/father_of_fractal_geometry_passes_\
at_age_85.html"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", and many other places. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4964214754747305`*^9, 3.496421517494932*^9}, {
   3.4964217078079615`*^9, 3.4964217101111917`*^9}, {3.4964217703512993`*^9, 
   3.4964217951812997`*^9}, {3.496422133032484*^9, 3.4964223091000896`*^9}, {
   3.496424354967656*^9, 3.496424388245983*^9}, 3.49642480675883*^9, {
   3.49649231246848*^9, 3.496492316296874*^9}, 3.4964923527681923`*^9}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In his seminal account, ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["The Fractal Geometry of Nature",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.amazon.com/Fractal-Geometry-Nature-Benoit-Mandelbrot/dp/\
B0006TZPW8/wolframresearch-20"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "http://www.amazon.com/Fractal-Geometry-Nature-Benoit-Mandelbrot/dp/\
B0006TZPW8/wolframresearch-20"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (1982), Mandelbrot generalized the concept of dimension to include \
fractional values, which could be used to describe irregular geometric shapes \
such as coastlines, clouds, and charts of stock prices. Fractal geometry is \
still not accepted as a rigorous subject by some mathematicians, who regard \
some of its constructs as \"pathological\". By his own account, Mandelbrot \
traced the origin of his concept of fractals to a question he first \
encountered as a student: How long is the coastline of Britain? He was \
surprised to discover that this depends on the scale and resolution of the \
map one is looking at. One map may show a fairly smooth representation of the \
coastline, but zooming in to a finer scale will reveal jagged edges that add \
up to a longer coastline. And zooming in further leads to an even longer \
coastline. In the 1950s, Mandelbrot proposed a new way to quantify the \
boundary curve of such irregular objects. He defined the fractal dimension, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"D", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     UnderscriptBox["lim", 
      RowBox[{"\[Epsilon]", "\[Rule]", "0"}]], 
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{"log", " ", 
       RowBox[{"N", "(", "\[Epsilon]", ")"}]}], 
      RowBox[{"log", "(", 
       RowBox[{"1", "/", "\[Epsilon]"}], ")"}]]}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " , where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"N", "(", "\[Epsilon]", ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " is the number of self-similar pieces of size ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[Epsilon]", TraditionalForm]]],
 " needed to approximate the whole structure. (This is closely analogous to \
the Hausdorff dimension for metric spaces.) The consensus result for the \
fractal dimension of the British coastline is around 1.26, which can be \
interpreted as about one-fourth of the way between a one- and a \
two-dimensional boundary."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.496666580162261*^9, {3.4966666186662035`*^9, 3.4966666435750036`*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Many of us at ",
 ButtonBox["Wolfram Research",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.wolfram.com/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://www.wolfram.com/"],
 " have written about fractals. The ",
 ButtonBox["Wolfram Demonstrations Project",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/"],
 " has ",
 ButtonBox["170 fractal Demonstrations",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/search.html?query=fractal"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/search.html?query=fractal"],
 " at the moment. Michael Trott has detailed many fractals in his ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["Mathematica GuideBooks",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.mathematicaguidebooks.org/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://www.mathematicaguidebooks.org/"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". For example, below is a fractal based on Gaussian maps."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4964224718783655`*^9, 3.4964225065498323`*^9}, {
   3.4964225489310703`*^9, 3.49642254893307*^9}, {3.4964226748276587`*^9, 
