Cell[TextData[{
 "Here's ",
 ButtonBox["Stephen Wolfram",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.stephenwolfram.com/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://www.stephenwolfram.com/"],
 ", from ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["A New Kind of Science",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www.wolframscience.com/nksonline/page-0934b-text"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://www.wolframscience.com/nksonline/page-0934b-text"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", page 934: \"The Mandelbrot set introduced by Beno\[IHat]t Mandelbrot in \
1979 is defined as the set of values of ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " for which such Julia sets are connected. This turns out to be equivalent \
to the set of values of ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " for which starting at ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 0 the inverse mapping ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " ",
 "\[Rule]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{" ", 
    SuperscriptBox["z", "2"]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " + ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " leads only to bounded values of ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". The Mandelbrot set turns out to have many intricate features which have \
been widely reproduced for their aesthetic value, as well as studied by \
mathematicians. The first picture below shows the overall form of the set; \
subsequent pictures show successive magnifications of the regions indicated. \
All parts of the Mandelbrot set are known to be connected. The whole set is \
not self-similar. However, as seen in the third and fourth pictures, within \
the set are isolated small copies of the whole set. In addition, as seen in \
the last picture, near most values of ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " the boundary of the Mandelbrot set looks very much like the Julia set for \
that value of ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".\""
}], "Text"],

